description.text:
This is a lightweight flexible shaft extruder, that i designed for highspeed printing.
The idea was to keep the stepper away from the moving parts so not too much mass has to be accelerated without the disadvantages of a bowden-extruder. (i posted a early idea of ot here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6653)
Another idea was to replace the passive idler bearing with a active second hobbed-thing as well as using gears with a bigger diameter to garanty better grip when extruding at high speed. Also the distance between the gears and the nozzle is relativel short for more direct drive.
The extreuder consists of two parts, each of which can rotate around the worm-axis. this way the distance between the worm and the gears always stays the same, but the pressure for driving the filament can be adjusted.
The name slugstruder is because of two reasons. in germany we call wormgears something like snail-gears (Schneckengetriebe) and slugs are something like snails as well. Another reason is that i like brainslugs ;) The flex-shaft i will use is one from a motorbike - speedo. These have one prefered direction to rotatet, so be sure to pick one that has the same rotation as the worm gear that u're using. If the torque for thsi one is not enough i will try a dremel like one later. This is a work in progress.
The parts i added are only to take a look at the design and do not work till now (the spring tensioner thing and some holes are still missing)
also the connection to the flexshaft is missing..
The gears are some standard parts that should be available everywhere.
The bigger holes are teardrop shaped to improve printability, but i could also supply some files with round holes.

Now that I have a grand old time with some bad acid reflux, I find it necessary to keep a bottle of 1000mg Tums on me at all times. I got mine here, which are uncommon on their website because it is a bulk surplus purchase, and they usually have imperial measurements only.
http://www.kjmagnetics.com/proddetail.asp?prod=ZD4
1/8" x 1/16" is the closest imperial equivalent and should also work, may be a bit of a tighter squeeze but the tolerance of the hole diameter should still be good enough for that. So for anyone looking to make a smaller and cheaper order with imperial magnets, try this link

Post Processing-
Step 1: Sand any rough spots to your liking
Step 2: Prime it with plastic primer, letting it dry completely between coats
Step 3: Paint everything but the body (my wife used a airbrush)
Step 4: Mask off the painted areas, leaving only the main body unpainted
Step 5: Paint the main body (my wife used black spray paint)
Step 6: Once dry, spray with a glossy finish to get the nice shiny look

description.text:
I didn't know...

... if someone has already print my original version and since the spiral block is the only part that is re-used, I decided to make it a V 2.0 now..

Concerning to my original version, the spiral got deeper as well as the teeth of the claws.
I also made the claws longer so that they won't jam if you push them together. Therefore, I enlarged the side holes of the turntable, so the claws can run out of it. This makes the gripping area much wider. They're also flatened so you don't need supports

print settings are like the old version but maybe you want to play around with them.

Sadly, I forgot to take a picture of the new version.. this will follow

How to build it

All you need is a bunch of M4 screws and maybe a M4 nut.
The axis is a M4x60 screw. I took one with conic head since they are smaller than lense heads or cylindric ones.

Push it through the turn table and then put the claws in. try to push them as close to the center as possible.
Next, put the spiral block on the screw and turn it until it engages with the claws teeth. Fix it with a nut and try to turn it. If the claws don't close evenly, try to exchange two of them.

Then fix the spiral block with three m4 screws on the axis.
Last step is to put some screws into the holes of the turntable to fix the claws positions when holding a coil corpus.

The Prusa i3 is still very new, and lacked a good single-hotend mount. I designed this mount for the Ubis hot end to work with my self-sourced Prusa i3 using 1.75 mm filament. The Ubis hot end has a groove that is mostly compatible with the J-head, at least according to google searches. This means that this mount should be fully compatible with J-head grooves as well. Included are two hot end mount variants, and a cold end bracket. For the hot end mount, I initially chose the screw hole hot end mount method that most extruders use. However, after reading this thread: http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?1,238528, I decided that a tight fitting groove mount made more sense, and redesigned my mount. Both versions are included. It is possible to adjust the height and depth of the mount, all accessible in the included SCAD files. The cold end mount attaches to the Prusa i3 sgraber frame, and holds the cold end up. I recommend this extruder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:34503. For the referenced pneumatic fittings, you should either print that extruder with a 5mm hole, or melt an M5 nut into the cavity. Remember to adjust the filament_diameter to 1.75mm.

Hot end mount (groovemount)
===
BOM:
  • 2x 5mm thread 4mm OD pneumatic pushfit connector, $5.14: (http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B009EO6A66/ref=oh_details_o01_s00_i00?ie=UTF8&psc=1)
  • 2 feet 4mm OD 2mm ID PTFE tube, $5.00: (http://shop.seemecnc.com/2mm-ID-x-4mm-OD-PTFE-Tube-BY-THE-FOOT-58708.htm)
  • 1x 40mm fan
  • 1x M5 nut (hardware store)
  • 4x M3 nuts
  • 4x M3 x 16mm screws
  • 4x M3 x 25mm screws
    • Print the hotend mount with ABS at least 2 perimeters. Do not use PLA! It may soften and lose grip on the hot end. Once it is printed, ream out all the M3 screw holes, and melt the M5 nut into the top of the mount. Screw the pneumatic fitting into the nut. Gently wedge the hot end into the mount. The groovemount plate should gently slide into the groove on the hot end. Align the M3 screw holes, and clamp the groove plate to the mount using the 16mm M3 nuts and screws. Screw the mount into the x-carriage with the 25mm screws. Align the 40mm fan with the two extra holes in the front, and screw them directly into the plastic using 25mm screws. Cold end mount
    ===
    The cold end mount is meant for the single-plate prusa i3 with the sgraber wings. It should not require any additional hardware. Loosen the top left z-axis smooth-rod holder. Slide the mount over the frame, aligning the holes with the existing screw holes for the z-axis holder. Screw the holder back onto the frame. Clean up the slot for the pneumatic fitting and the M4 screw, then slide the extruder into the mount. Tighten the M4 screw to stabilize it.

description.text:
Hi there!
this is my current project, an automatic coil winder. It's controlled by an arduino uno, so you just have to choose your number of windings and start it.

What you need is an Arduino Uno (or similar) and a SainSmart LCD Keypad Shield
http://www.sainsmart.com/sainsmart-uno-r3-lcd1602-keypad-shield-starter-kit-for-arduino-mega328p-au.html

Additionally, there are two little modules to solder (or maybe you can buy some?) which are a motor driver (basically, a BS170 mosfet and two resistors) and a light switch (which too only needs two resistors). I Built it on stripe grid pcb.

You will also need three 624ZZ bearings.

And you will need a 37mm geared motor like this one:
http://de.aliexpress.com/store/product/DC-12V-motor-37GB-37MM-300RPM-High-powered-Torque-8-5KG-CM-high-torque-gear-box/1549033_32320818214.html

I've put my clumsy source code into this thing and will rework it asap.

Oh er.. you will need 12V power, too ;)

Just mount the motor into the motor stand. Leave the lower two screw holes free because they would disturb your light switch. Mount the stand on a wooden plate and put the but the coupling on the shaft (encoder wheel towards the motor) and fix it with two m3 screws.
Leave some space towards the motor stand so you can put the light switch inside later.
next, put a bearing into the bearingmount and put the three jaw chuck on it. Put the shaft of the chuck on the coupling and fix the bearingmount on the plate.

Now put two bearings into the idler wheel and screw it to the idler mount. mount it on the plate but leave some space towards the chuck. (i got about 15cm which seems to work)

you will also need something to hold your wire.. haven't yet built something, just got a screw for it.

use it

  • fix a coil corpus on the chuck
  • turn the wire two times around the coupling
  • thread the wire through the small hole at the lower side of the corpus
  • switch the machine on
  • choose your number of windings (left/right for decimal point choice, up/down for increment/decrement, select to start)
  • hold the end of the wire for a while to make shure that the wire stays where it has to..
  • wait until your windings are done..

Yet another one of these things to hold one end of the Y-axis belt for Prusa Mendel. It is designed to have a low profile and does not bend the belt.

Instructions

Print the base part, and the slider either for T5 or T2.5. I have only tested the T2.5 live, but it is probably the most challenging.
As it's name implies the slider should slide freely within the base. It can be sanded to fit.
Pass a 20mm M3 bolt through the hole in the end of the base, and screw a nut on it. It's a little fiddly, but easy enough. Only screw the bolt in the width of the nut, and then pull it back until the nut is in the nut trap.
Then bolt the base in place at the end of the lower plate. Pass the belt through it, and lay it in the slider. Make sure the dimple in the slider is facing the bolt, because it has extra plastic to take the pressure.
Draw the slider back into the base as far as it goes and attach the other end of the belt with the usual components, pulling it snug tight around the idler and drive gear.
The photos should show the sequence (except that it is not bolted down during assembly).
Further tension can be achieved by tightening the bolt. A hex head bolt is best because you can use a ball drive and get a little off centre, out from under the belt.

• KIT 1 -
    Moteur Stirling en KIT de type gamma.
    Conception et réalisation du kit présenté : Alain Ducros
    Le kit permet de réaliser un moteur Stirling ludique sur le principe d'un lego composé principalement de pièces imprimées, de récupération de boites alimentaires classiques et de quelques pièces courantes de quincaillerie.

Particularité du kit :

  • L'assemblage n'est pas figé à une dimension, il s'adapte aux boites alimentaires, avec différentes variantes d'assemblage en fonction de ses choix et des diverses récupérations.
  • Le sous ensemble vilebrequin et volant d'inertie est réglable, on peut choisir la course du piston en fonction de la boite récupérée.
  • Le volant d'inertie est réglable par ajout de poids.
  • Le bras de manivelle est réglable par des « manetons » coulissants ou des emplacements de fixations suivant un pas figé.
  • le flasque supérieur du vilebrequin permet de recevoir plusieurs diamètres d'axe et de faire un montage avec ou sans roulement.
  • L'ensemble complet est assemblé par plusieurs tiges filetées qui se positionnent dans différentes positions de trous ou d'oblongs en fonction du diamètre des boites.

Ce concepts permet de faire des tests et de s'adapter au matériel récupéré mais il reste délicat à démarrer : il faut assurer un minimum de contraintes et une étanchéité parfaite.
Ici, les pièces sont en PLA ou ABS et le piston déplaceur est en tissu abrasif, l'apport d’énergie se limite donc à quelques flammes de bougie.

comments.text: Be careful with those ones. I have some very similar diodes which just use a resistor instead of a propper regulator. Absolutely under no circumstances power them for more than a millisecond pulse with more than 3.0v. 3.3v will burn them out after a few seconds or maybe a minute or so. If you want to make it work on more variable power supplies you could supply their power using an LED driver, like those found on addressable RGB strips. You'll need to configure it to not exceed the power specification of the laser module. Looks like for the ones you bought this power usage is 40ma max, so if you use a driver like the ws2811's that are pretty popular now, that should keep things nice and safe with a wide margin. Plus you can write colours to several lasers in series if you like using only one pin of a microcontroller. ^_^

Are you using your notebook as your main computer? Are you fed up with having to fiddle around with multiple plugs and cables every time you want to take your notebook with you? Are you annoyed with the cable clutter on your desk? HackDock to the rescue! Build your very own customizable docking solution tailored to your notebook and your needs with a 3d printer and some Sugru. The HackDock is geared towards MacBook but will work with many other notebooks, too. It consists of two parts: The connector (this Thing) which combines all your plugs into one consolidated big one you can easily attach and detach and the Base Unit (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:143161) in which you can dump your peripheral components like USB Hubs or even an external HDD. The Base Unit can then be mounted out of sight under your desk or behind your monitor (neat!).

I designed the HackDock as part of a student project during my masters program in Human Computer Interaction, so some effort went into documenting and explaining everything thoroughly in the form of an accompanying blog:
http://scriptogr.am/oliverstickel/the-hackdock
If you are interested in the HackDock and/or making one, the blog is the way to go - you will find a more extensive overview as well as prerequisites, measuring, printing and assembling instructions over there. For those of you who are interested, there's also a bit of documentation about the design progress.

I've been using the HackDock for weeks now and I'm very happy with the way it works and enables me to have neat and organized desk - judge for yourselves based on the photos in the gallery (more in the blog). :) I hope, there are some people here who also like the concept and decide to build a HackDock - if you do, I'd really love to hear about your opinions and experiences!

remixed_from.title: Sailing ship for table top games

description.text:
After a bit of poking around with the Sea-Ghost RPG sailing ship for a remix request, i decided to re-remix it to how I wanted it to be set up for game play.

There is now 4 or 5 different options (at the time of this initial upload) for this rather nifty sailing vessel model by a few different individuals here. If you print this, please upload a photo. If you run into errors message me and i'll see about fixing it.

This edit/remix of the Sea Ghost was done entirely in Blender3d using the base files for the Sailing Ship. The masts are available from the original item file, Shown under sources.

The Mermaid figurehead is also posted separately as its own item. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1430885

My thought is to bond all three bases together making a tray. the upper decks have a grooved edge to allow them to sit tightly onto the tray base. The entire upper structure is able to come off in pieces to allow a variety of levels of access during game play.

There is a piece in here as a mast support that will need to be bonded to the lower center section.

Edit: Error on My part. Fixed the issue, re-exported and reuploaded all files.
I am sorry for any inconvenience this has caused, and thank you for pointing it out.

Edit2: added generic_hatch Frame and Hatch Cover so that any part of the inner deck can be cut out and turned into an access panel. Generic hatch frame has been made to a slightly greater thickness of the stern deck panel. Hatch just sits in the frame, hinges if wanted will have to be a DIY item. A ladder would be the access item to the under deck.

Edit3: Increased Deck thicknesses, as well as depth of the Generic hatch cover, its frame, and the Hatch for the cargo hold in the center section.

Bow_Base_2 and Bow_Cabin_2 are not interchangle with the original, both are left on here. The revision 2 has the join of the bowsprit section meeting at the lower intersection of the joint groove. The original is at the upper intersection of the joint groove. If you are printing the original support will be needed, although you might want it anyway on the upper sections for the joint groove. See the comment section.

Stern_Cabin_2 had its inner deck support lip lowered to match the new thickness of that deck.

edit 4: Bow Base "repaired" has been ran through netfabb to fix a slicing issue that shows up in Cura which sliced the model part as a solid object. both files are going to be left up so check which one your attempting to print.

Building the quadcopter

The FPV racing quadcopter is one of the best experience you can get from RC Toys. this instructable will explain how you can build your own 250 class racing quadcopter, with FPV system to place your eyes in the sky..

Building the quadcopter
the first step of building the quadcopter is building the frame, just follow the instractions you got with the frame and build all the chassis.

The quadcopter includes 4 motors, 2 CW motors and 2 CCW motors, the motors installation order:

front left arm - CW motor
front right arm - CCW motor
rear left arm - CCW motor
rear right motor - CW motor

when you install the motors, point the wires to the arm of the chassis.

the ESC has 5 wires and a plug, the 3 black wires needs to be connected to the motors.
for CW rotation you need to connect the wires straight from the esc to the motor (first ESC wire to first motor wire, second wire to second wire, third wire to third wire). for the CCW rotation you just need to switch between the second to the third wire. (first ESC wire to first motor wire, second wire to third wire, third wire to second wire)

connect and solder all the ESC red wires together to the T-plug red wire, and the black wires to the black one.

after you make all the connections with solder, you can connect the flight controller.

connect the ESC to the cc3d in this order

connect the motor output 1 to the front left ESC
connect the motor output 2 to the front right ESC
connect the motor output 3 to the rear left ESC
connect the motor output 4 to the rear right ESC

Connect the 2.4Ghz reciever to the CC3D flight controller, just plug the connections from the reciever output to the cc3d inputs, (channel 1 to input 1, channel 2 to input 2, etc..) you need to connect at least 6 channels.

This is all the wiring you neet to make for the quadcopter, when you finish the wiring you need to update the cc3d firmware and make a calibration. the CC3D flight controller works with the exelent opensource openpilot program.
download the software and install it to your pc, follow the instructions in the open pilot UI and make the installation.

title: MPCNC Tool Holder Nut Trap for 19mm ID pipe

description.text:
I needed MPCNC Tool Holder Nut Traps to suit my 19mm ID (25mm x 3mm wall thickness Aluminium pipe), and the stock units were too big (designed for 1mm wall thickness by the looks).

Just printed two of them and they fit nice 'n' snug (usual deal with cleaning out the holes with a 4mm drill bit, and sanding/scraping off the flattened first layer). I have not designed in any clearance for the nut traps as I wanted them to stay put. The nuts pull in fine using 4mm screws.

Hope someone else finds them useful.

The OEM part has snap-in tangs on the three prongs (they broke on my car's stock part, which is what prompted this Thing). The prongs are very fragile and tend to break during support removal if you're not careful, but they're not really necessary anyway.  
The stock part has an o-ring, and this Thing includes a recess for it.
